<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="11">
This species differs from other Palaearctic species of the genus by having forewings with two submarginal cells (versus three cells in other species, except 
<taxonomicName family="Apidae" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. bischoffi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="11" rank="species" species="bischoffi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="11">E. bischoffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mavromoustakis, 1954) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Epeolus leleji sp. nov., holotype, male A, B habitus, lateral view (A); dorsal view (B). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.84.67150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578840" pageId="0" pageNumber="11">2A, B</figureCitation>
). The new species are clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName family="Apidae" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. bischoffi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="11" rank="species" species="bischoffi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="11">E. bischoffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by lack of long black dense hair on the whole body, position of labral teeth closer to apical margin, the reddish female mesosoma (black in 
<taxonomicName family="Apidae" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. bischoffi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="11" rank="species" species="bischoffi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="11">E. bischoffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and many other characters.
</paragraph>
